      "hash": "5a368372c4a6899011015b037604bf2234882b7939dedebb24b061ea1483e105",
      "result": "## Research Summary: `@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows` v2.9.0\n\n### What it does\nDynamic workflow orchestration for Pi — fan tasks across subagents with real model routing, token accounting, resume, and interactive TUI. Claude Code-style, production-grade.\n\n### Config options\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `~/.pi/workflows/settings.json` | Global settings, custom `keywordTriggerWord` |\n| `~/.pi/workflows/model-tiers.json` | Map small/medium/big → real models |\n| `~/.pi/workflows/projects/<project>/` | Per-project run history, saved workflows |\n\nTrigger control: `/workflows-trigger on|off|status|set <word>`\n\n### Key APIs\n\n**Globals for workflow scripts:**\n- `agent(prompt, opts)` — spawn subagent (tier, model, schema, isolation)\n- `parallel(thunks)` — concurrent fan-out\n- `pipeline(items, ...stages)` — sequential stages\n- `phase(title, {budget?})` — group agents, optional token cap\n- `checkpoint(prompt, opts)` — human approval gate\n- `budget` — `{total, spent(), remaining()}` real-time tracker\n\n**Built-in quality patterns:** `verify`, `judgePanel`, `loopUntilDry`, `completenessCheck`\n\n**Agent options:** `tier`, `model`, `agentType`, `isolation: \"worktree\"`, `schema`, `retries`, `label`, `phase`\n\n### Commands\n```\n/workflows                    interactive navigator\n/workflows status <id>        watch live\n/workflows save <name>        save as reusable command\n/workflows run <prompt>       force from prompt\n/workflows-trigger off|on     keyword control\n/workflows-models             map tiers to models\n/deep-research <question>     web research + cross-check\n/adversarial-review <task>    skeptical review\n/multi-perspective \"<topic>\"  multi-angle analysis\n```\n\n### Pi integration\n- Registered via `pi.extensions: [\"extensions/workflow.ts\"]` in package.json\n- Adds `workflow` tool + slash commands to Pi\n- Uses Pi sessions for subagent isolation\n- Hooks Pi TUI for live progress panel\n- Stores state in `~/.pi/workflows/` (not per-project `.pi/`)\n- Respects Pi's model auth for provider routing"
    },
    {
      "index": 2,
      "hash": "b66bdd6ec1dba3655d83f7e1ed51452d6171a4b4452a793b54eee3ad0fd7cf08",
      "result": "## Research Summary\n\n### GitNexus Skills\n\n`pi-gitnexus` (v0.6.4) has **5 skills** — all codebase analysis, zero workflow-related:\n\n| Skill | Purpose |\n|-------|---------|\n| `gitnexus-debugging` | Trace errors via `gitnexus_query` → `gitnexus_context` → source files |\n| `gitnexus-exploring` | Codebase exploration via `gitnexus_list_repos` → `gitnexus_query` → `gitnexus_context` |\n| `gitnexus-impact-analysis` | Blast radius via `gitnexus_impact` → `gitnexus_detect_changes` |\n| `gitnexus-pr-review` | PR review combining impact + context |\n| `gitnexus-refactoring` | Safe rename/extract/move using `gitnexus_rename` + Cypher |\n\n**No workflow-related skills in pi-gitnexus.** All use knowledge graph tools (`gitnexus_*`) for code analysis.\n\n---\n\n### Dynamic Workflow Packages (installed)\n\nTwo packages provide dynamic workflow capabilities:\n\n**1. `@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows` (v2.9.0)**\n- Provides `workflow` tool (JS sandbox with `agent()`/`parallel()`/`pipeline()`/`phase()`)\n- Keywords: `workflow` or `workflows` in any message auto-arms workflow mode\n- Commands: `/workflows`, `/deep-research`, `/adversarial-review`, `/ultracode`\n- Settings: `~/.pi/workflows/settings.json` (keyword trigger, etc.)\n- Extension: `extensions/workflow.ts`\n- Journaled + replayable runs, per-agent model routing\n\n**2. `@mediadatafusion/pi-workflow-suite` (v0.0.23)**\n- Structured orchestration: 4 modes (Idle, Standard, Plan, Mission)\n- Role-specific model routing: planner, executor, reviewer, validator\n- Config: `~/.pi/agent/workflow-settings.json`\n- Skills: `codebase-discovery`, `find-skills`, `git-safe-summary`, `implementation-planning`, `project-rules-audit`, `safe-execution`, `validation-review`\n- Extensions: `workflow-modes.ts` (1.48MB), `workflow-model-router.ts`, `workflow-state.ts`, `workflow-tool-guard.ts`, etc.\n\n---\n\n### Local Config Files\n\n| Path | Content |\n|------|---------|\n| `~/.pi/agent/workflow-settings.json` | Full workflow suite config (models, workflow gates, standard/plan/mission settings) |\n| `~/.pi/agent/workflows/active.json` | Active workflow state: `{\"mode\": \"idle\", \"updatedAt\": \"2026-06-30T17:13:33.976Z\"}` |\n| `~/.pi/workflows/projects/` | Per-project workflow runs (current project: `pmigov-82340f88a085`, run: `mr0xqzdh-a8djmf`) |\n| `~/.pi/agent/morph.json` | Morph plugin config (routing, stats, compaction) |\n\n---\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nDynamic workflows come from two **installed packages**, not from pi-gitnexus. pi-gitnexus is purely code graph analysis. The workflow tool in this session is powered by `@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows` (provides the `workflow` tool + `agent()`/`parallel()` API) and `@mediadatafusion/pi-workflow-suite` (adds structured modes, model routing, and plan/execute/review gates)."
    },
    {
      "index": 1,
      "hash": "64e93c165701c7da325751d7a8e7c052446cad2fba62922849f1d57bbbafc47e",
      "result": "## Research Complete: pi-dynamic-workflows Ecosystem\n\n**Key Findings:**\n\n1. **pi-dynamic-workflows package** exists at `/home/yash/.dotfiles/pi/.pi/agent/npm/node_modules/@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows`\n   - Version 2.9.0, MIT licensed\n   - Claude Code–style dynamic workflows for Pi\n   - npm: `@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows`\n\n2. **Core concept**: JavaScript orchestration scripts (`.dwf.ts`) that spawn subagents in parallel, keep intermediate results in script variables (not chat context), return only results.\n\n3. **Key APIs**:\n   - `agent(prompt, opts)` - spawn isolated subagent\n   - `parallel(thunks)` - run multiple agents concurrently\n   - `pipeline(items, ...stages)` - multi-stage fan-out\n   - `phase(title)` - group agents in live view\n   - `verify/judgePanel/loopUntilDry/completenessCheck` - quality patterns\n\n4. **Agent options**:\n   - `tier`: \"small\" | \"medium\" | \"big\" - model routing\n   - `model`: exact provider/modelId\n   - `agentType`: named definition from `.pi/agents/`\n   - `isolation: \"worktree\"` - git worktree isolation\n   - `schema`: JSON Schema for structured output\n\n5. **pi-crew dynamic workflows** also found at `/home/yash/.dotfiles/pi/.pi/agent/npm/node_modules/pi-crew/docs/dynamic-workflows.md`\n   - Similar concept but part of pi-crew package\n   - Uses `ctx.agent()`, `ctx.fanOut()`, `ctx.pipeline()`\n\n6. **Pi coding agent** has built-in workflow support via extensions (subagent example shows chained workflows)\n\n**Installation**: `pi install npm:@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows` then `/reload`\n\n**Commands**: `/workflows`, `/deep-research`, `/adversarial-review`, `/ultracode`, `/effort`\n\n**Storage**: `~/.pi/workflows/` (global), project-scoped under `~/.pi/workflows/projects/<project>/`"
    },
    {
      "index": 3,
      "hash": "6385e46a4e249a8fa5cc8dac550e33e499784ee5ebac7af3a1a656499ab16a3e",
      "result": {
        "summary": "`@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows` is Pi extension for running Claude Code–style dynamic workflows: JavaScript orchestration scripts spawn isolated subagents, route them to model tiers, run them in parallel/pipelines, group work into phases, track tokens, resume/watch runs, and return compact results instead of dumping all intermediate context into chat.",
        "guide": "## 1. Core purpose\n\nUse plugin when task benefits from fan-out/fan-in:\n\n- parallel repo inspection\n- multi-perspective review\n- research + verification\n- staged implementation planning\n- adversarial review\n- repeatable workflows saved as commands\n\nMain value: orchestration logic lives in script variables. Subagent chatter stays outside main chat context. Final result comes back small.\n\n## 2. Install + configure\n\nInstall:\n\n```bash\npi install npm:@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows\n```\n\nThen reload Pi:\n\n```text\n/reload\n```\n\nPackage registers extension like:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"pi\": {\n    \"extensions\": [\"extensions/workflow.ts\"]\n  }\n}\n```\n\nImportant paths:\n\n| Path | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `~/.pi/workflows/settings.json` | global workflow settings, keyword trigger word |\n| `~/.pi/workflows/model-tiers.json` | maps `small` / `medium` / `big` tiers to real models |\n| `~/.pi/workflows/projects/<project>/` | per-project run history + saved workflows |\n\nUseful commands:\n\n```text\n/workflows                       # interactive navigator\n/workflows status <id>           # watch live run\n/workflows save <name>           # save current/generated workflow\n/workflows run <prompt>          # force workflow from prompt\n/workflows-trigger on|off|status # keyword trigger control\n/workflows-trigger set <word>    # custom keyword\n/workflows-models                # configure tier -> model routing\n/deep-research <question>        # built-in research workflow\n/adversarial-review <task>       # skeptical review workflow\n/multi-perspective \"<topic>\"     # multi-angle analysis\n```\n\n## 3. Key concepts\n\n### Workflow script format\n\nWorkflow scripts are JavaScript orchestration files. In Pi tool form, script must start with metadata:\n\n```js\nexport const meta = {\n  name: 'repo_review',\n  description: 'Review repo with parallel specialists',\n  phases: [{ title: 'Inspect' }, { title: 'Synthesize' }],\n};\n```\n\nThen call workflow globals:\n\n- `agent(prompt, opts)` — spawn subagent\n- `parallel(thunks)` — run thunks concurrently\n- `pipeline(items, ...stages)` — run staged work per item\n- `phase(title, { budget? })` — group agents in live UI, optional token cap\n- `checkpoint(prompt, opts)` — human approval gate\n- `budget` — token tracker: `spent()`, `remaining()`\n\nQuality helpers:\n\n- `verify(item, { reviewers, threshold, lens })`\n- `judgePanel(attempts, { judges, rubric })`\n- `loopUntilDry({ round, key, consecutiveEmpty })`\n- `completenessCheck(args, results)`\n\n### `agent(prompt, opts)`\n\nUse for isolated subtask. Good options:\n\n```js\nawait agent('Inspect auth flow. Return risks only.', {\n  label: 'auth inspect',\n  tier: 'small',\n  agentType: 'researcher',\n  schema: {\n    type: 'object',\n    properties: {\n      risks: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' } },\n    },\n    required: ['risks'],\n  },\n});\n```\n\nCommon options:\n\n| Option | Use |\n|---|---|\n| `label` | short unique UI/status name |\n| `tier` | `small`, `medium`, `big` model routing |\n| `model` | exact provider/model ID; overrides tier |\n| `agentType` | named role like planner/researcher/reviewer |\n| `schema` | JSON Schema for machine-readable output |\n| `isolation: \"worktree\"` | separate git worktree for parallel edit work |\n| `retries` | retry recoverable agent failures |\n| `phase` | place agent in phase without separate `phase()` call |\n\n### `parallel(thunks)`\n\nTakes functions, not promises.\n\nCorrect:\n\n```js\nconst results = await parallel(\n  areas.map((area) => () =>\n    agent(`Inspect ${area}. Return concise findings.`, {\n      label: `${area} inspect`,\n      tier: 'small',\n    })\n  )\n);\n```\n\nWrong:\n\n```js\nawait parallel(areas.map((area) => agent(`Inspect ${area}`)));\n```\n\n### `pipeline(items, ...stages)`\n\nUse when each item needs ordered stages, while items can still run concurrently.\n\n```js\nconst reviewed = await pipeline(\n  files,\n  async (file) => agent(`Summarize ${file}`, { label: `sum ${file}`, tier: 'small' }),\n  async (summary, file) => agent(`Review summary for ${file}: ${summary}`, { label: `review ${file}`, tier: 'medium' })\n);\n```\n\n### `phase(title)`\n\nUse phases for live TUI grouping and budgets.\n\n```js\nphase('Inspect');\nconst findings = await parallel([...]);\n\nphase('Synthesize', { budget: 20_000 });\nconst final = await agent(`Synthesize: ${JSON.stringify(findings)}`, {\n  label: 'final synth',\n  tier: 'big',\n});\n```\n\nIf `meta.phases` declares phases, call `phase('Exact Title')` before work in each phase.",
        "examples": "## Example 1: minimal fan-out repo review\n\n```js\nexport const meta = {\n  name: 'quick_repo_review',\n  description: 'Parallel repo review with synthesis',\n  phases: [{ title: 'Inspect' }, { title: 'Synthesize' }],\n};\n\nphase('Inspect');\nconst areas = ['auth', 'data flow', 'UI', 'tests'];\n\nconst findings = await parallel(\n  areas.map((area) => () =>\n    agent(`Inspect ${area}. Return top 3 concrete findings with file paths.`, {\n      label: `${area} review`,\n      tier: 'small',\n      agentType: 'reviewer',\n      schema: {\n        type: 'object',\n        properties: {\n          findings: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'string' } },\n        },\n        required: ['findings'],\n      },\n    })\n  )\n);\n\nphase('Synthesize');\nreturn await agent(`Merge findings, dedupe, rank by risk: ${JSON.stringify(findings)}`, {\n  label: 'risk synth',\n  tier: 'big',\n});\n```\n\n## Example 2: research + adversarial verification\n\n```js\nexport const meta = {\n  name: 'verified_research',\n  description: 'Research question, cross-check claims, return grounded answer',\n  phases: [{ title: 'Research' }, { title: 'Verify' }, { title: 'Answer' }],\n};\n\nphase('Research');\nconst angles = ['official docs', 'source code', 'known issues'];\nconst notes = await parallel(\n  angles.map((angle) => () =>\n    agent(`Research ${angle} for: ${args.question}. Cite sources.`, {\n      label: angle,\n      tier: 'medium',\n      agentType: 'researcher',\n    })\n  )\n);\n\nphase('Verify');\nconst checked = await verify(notes, {\n  reviewers: 3,\n  threshold: 2,\n  lens: 'Find unsupported claims, version mismatches, and contradictions.',\n});\n\nphase('Answer');\nreturn await agent(`Write concise practical answer from verified notes: ${JSON.stringify(checked)}`, {\n  label: 'final answer',\n  tier: 'big',\n});\n```\n\n## Example 3: staged file analysis with `pipeline`\n\n```js\nexport const meta = {\n  name: 'file_pipeline',\n  description: 'Summarize then review files',\n  phases: [{ title: 'Analyze' }],\n};\n\nphase('Analyze');\nreturn await pipeline(\n  args.files,\n  async (file) =>\n    agent(`Read ${file}. Summarize responsibilities and exports.`, {\n      label: `summ ${file}`,\n      tier: 'small',\n    }),\n  async (summary, file) =>\n    agent(`Review ${file} using this summary: ${summary}. Return only actionable issues.`, {\n      label: `review ${file}`,\n      tier: 'medium',\n      agentType: 'reviewer',\n    })\n);\n```\n\n## Example 4: human approval gate\n\n```js\nexport const meta = {\n  name: 'plan_then_execute',\n  description: 'Create plan, wait for approval, then implement',\n  phases: [{ title: 'Plan' }, { title: 'Execute' }],\n};\n\nphase('Plan');\nconst plan = await agent(`Plan minimal implementation for: ${args.task}`, {\n  label: 'impl plan',\n  tier: 'medium',\n  agentType: 'planner',\n});\n\nawait checkpoint(`Approve this plan?\\n\\n${plan}`, { label: 'approval' });\n\nphase('Execute');\nreturn await agent(`Implement approved plan:\\n${plan}`, {\n  label: 'implement',\n  tier: 'medium',\n  isolation: 'worktree',\n});\n```",
        "tips": "## Effective workflow patterns\n\n- Use workflows only when parallelism or repeatability pays. One quick edit does not need workflow.\n- Give every agent narrow scope and exact output shape.\n- Use `schema` for anything consumed by later steps.\n- Tag every agent with `tier`: `small` for inspection, `medium` for analysis, `big` for synthesis/judgment.\n- Keep prompts self-contained. Subagents do not automatically know parent context unless prompt gives it.\n- Use `parallel()` for independent branches. Use `pipeline()` for ordered stages per item.\n- Use final synthesis agent after fan-out. Raw arrays of subagent notes are rarely final output.\n- Use `verify` or adversarial reviewer for research, security, migration, or high-risk conclusions.\n- Use `checkpoint()` before destructive edits, expensive runs, or scope changes.\n- Use `isolation: \"worktree\"` when multiple agents may edit same repo in parallel.\n- Keep returned data compact. Store intermediate detail in variables, summarize at end.\n- Save repeated workflows with `/workflows save <name>`.\n- Watch long runs with `/workflows status <id>`.\n- Configure `/workflows-models` once so tiers route correctly.\n\n## Anti-patterns\n\n- Workflow for one file read or one simple bug fix.\n- Giant vague agent prompt: “analyze everything”. Split into narrow branches.\n- Passing promises to `parallel()` instead of thunks.\n- Declaring phases but never calling `phase()`.\n- No unique `label`; live UI becomes unreadable.\n- No `schema` while later code expects structured fields.\n- Using `big` tier for every branch. Wasteful.\n- Parallel edit agents without worktree isolation.\n- Assuming subagents share full chat/repo context. They need explicit instructions and paths.\n- Returning all intermediate notes directly to user. Synthesize and prune.",
        "gotchas": "## Gotchas + limitations\n\n- Dynamic workflows are from `@quintinshaw/pi-dynamic-workflows`, not `pi-gitnexus`. GitNexus provides code graph analysis skills/tools, not workflow orchestration.\n- Another installed package, `@mediadatafusion/pi-workflow-suite`, may add structured modes and gates. Do not confuse its `~/.pi/agent/workflow-settings.json` with dynamic workflow config in `~/.pi/workflows/`.\n- Storage is global under `~/.pi/workflows/`, with project-scoped subdirectories. It is not stored inside each repo by default.\n- Keyword trigger can auto-arm workflow mode when messages include `workflow` / `workflows`; disable or change via `/workflows-trigger` if annoying.\n- `parallel()` requires functions: `() => agent(...)`, not direct `agent(...)` calls.\n- Workflow scripts run in constrained JS environment. Avoid Node imports/FS assumptions unless plugin docs/runtime explicitly allow them.\n- `opts.model` overrides `opts.tier`; use exact model IDs only when needed.\n- Failed branches may return `null`; synthesis must tolerate missing results.\n- Token budgets help, but they are caps; over-tight budgets can kill useful branches.\n- Worktree isolation helps parallel edits but adds merge/reconciliation overhead.\n- Long workflows need labels and phases, otherwise status/debugging becomes painful.\n- Built-in commands like `/deep-research` and `/adversarial-review` are good defaults. Write custom workflow only when built-ins do not fit."
      }
    }
  ],
